  "prompt": "How do I write a PhD proposal?",
  "response": "Writing a PhD proposal involves several key steps:\n\n1. Structure\n- Title page\n- Abstract\n- Introduction\n- Research question/objectives\n- Literature review\n- Research methodology\n- Expected outcomes\n- Bibliography\n- Timeline\n\n2. Key Components\n- Clear, original research question\n- Demonstrate knowledge of existing research\n- Explain research significance\n- Outline feasible methodology\n- Show potential contribution to field\n\n3. Research Question\n- Specific and focused\n- Innovative\n- Researchable\n- Aligned with academic discipline\n\n4. Literature Review\n- Critically analyze existing research\n- Identify gaps in current knowledge\n- Show how your research will address these gaps\n\n5. Methodology\n- Describe research methods\n- Explain data collection techniques\n- Discuss research design\n- Justify chosen approaches\n\n6. Practical Considerations\n- Check university-specific guidelines\n- Be concise (typically 1500-3000 words)\n- Use academic language\n- Proofread carefully\n- Include realistic timeline and budget\n\n7. Additional Tips\n- Consult potential supervisors\n- Get feedback from peers/mentors\n- Demonstrate passion and expertise\n- Show research feasibility\n- Be clear and compelling",
